---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="Contribute">
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Contribute a question — or a whole path</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Every learning path on this site is a plain YAML file. No CMS, no
      database: if you can edit a text file, you can improve a path.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose">
    <h2>What a step looks like</h2>
    <pre><code>- slug: stats-essentials
  title: "Aggregating with stats"
  goal: "Use stats to count, sum and average events by field."
  prompt: |
    I'm learning Splunk step by step. So far I know how to search
    and work with fields. Act as my instructor and teach me the
    stats command... At the end, quiz me with 3 questions, one at
    a time, and wait for my answers.
  quiz_prompt: |
    Quiz me on the Splunk stats command — 5 questions, one at a
    time. Grade each answer and explain what I missed.
  practice: "Run a stats count by sourcetype on your own data."</code></pre>

    <h2>Ways to contribute</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Improve a prompt</strong> — found a phrasing that gets better
      answers from the AI? Edit the step and open a pull request.<br />
      <strong>Reorder steps</strong> — think concept B must come before
      concept A? PRs that change ordering should explain why in the
      description.<br />
      <strong>Fill a skeleton</strong> — Kubernetes, Docker and Linux are
      outlined but unwritten. Pick a module and write its steps.<br />
      <strong>Propose a new topic</strong> — add a new YAML file under
      <code>content/topics/</code>.
    </p>

    <h2>Ground rules</h2>
    <p>
      Prompts must give the AI a tutor role (explain → quiz → wait for
      answers), must carry context ("so far I know…"), and must stay
      vendor-neutral — they should work in ChatGPT, Claude and Gemini alike.
      Ordering disputes are settled by maintainers after discussion in the PR.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      The GitHub repository link will appear here when the project goes
      public. For now the project lives on its author's home server.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
